<DOCID> 613 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 2, 1989, Monday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part 6; Page 1; Column 4; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
738 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOWARD ROSENBERG: POTOMAC 'POWER GAME' -- RULE NO. 1 IS . . . TAKE CARE OF NO. 
1 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HOWARD ROSENBERG 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What a thrill it is to visit Washington, stroll the Capitol, tour the great 
edifices of liberty, glory in the traditions of democracy and see the elected 
representatives of the people governing. 
</P>
<P>
Or whatever it is they do. 
</P>
<P>
"Before you save the world, you gotta save your seat," says California 
Congressman George Miller. 
</P>
<P>
Ah, yes. Down from the clouds we plummet, crashing into the hard tundra of 
political reality. Miller's pragmatic words, spoken on the premiere of a PBS 
series titled "The Power Game," epitomize what appears to be the primary 
mission of many, if not most members of Congress. Not survival of the universe. 
Not survival of the United States. 
</P>
<P>
Survival of self. 
</P>
<P>
Taking care of No. 1. That's the main theme of tonight's instructive hour about 
Congress (at 8 p.m. on Channels 28 and 15; 10 p.m. on Channel 24) opening this 
week's four-part series adapted from reporter/host Hedrick Smith's book about 
the inside workings of Washington. Tuesday's program tackles the Pentagon, 
Wednesday's, such unelected power brokers as the media and Thursday's, the 
presidency. 
</P>
<P>
The drive to remain in office is primordial in politics. Yet Smith credits the 
Congressional Class of '74 -- a group of reformers who changed the rules of the 
power game -- with perfecting the techniques of survival to the extent that we 
now may have only a three-day Congress. 
</P>
<P>
Many members remain in Washington only Tuesday through Thursday, spending the 
other days back home, protecting their incumbencies by informally stumping and 
raising the funds they need for their TV-minded reelection campaigns. The 
survival obsession may be steadier in the House, which has two-year terms, than 
in the Senate, whose members are elected every six years. Yet the obsession is 
shared by both bodies. 
</P>
<P>
The average Senate campaign alone costs $3 million, we're told. Handshakings 
and mailings help. But the cornerstone of the "constant campaign," as Smith 
labels it, is media exposure. 
</P>
<P>
"American politics is money and 30-second spots," laments former Missouri Sen. 
Thomas Eagleton. "The modern young candidates -- the Dick Gephardts, the Al 
Gores -- can talk in 10 seconds, 20 and 30. You just tell 'em what you want, 
and they go click, click, click, click. Old-fashioned politicians like me take 
three weeks to answer something." 
</P>
<P>
Or as former House Speaker Tip O'Neill's one-time media adviser Chris Matthews 
puts it: "The old guys schmooze, the new guys broadcast." 
</P>
<P>
And broadcast and broadcast. 
</P>
<P>
Smith sees New York Congressman (and Class of '74 member) Stephen J. Solarz as 
the prototypical media swifty and "master of all survival games." Regular 
viewers of network newscasts will attest to that. 
</P>
<P>
The Solarz mastery includes making an impression on the folks back home by 
shrewdly getting his mug on camera for positive reasons again and again. That 
includes this program, ironically, for even as his power game is being replayed 
and critically analyzed by Smith, the media-smart Solarz uses the camera to 
impressively convey action, movement and concern. 
</P>
<P>
The vast majority of Congress with less access to national TV than Solarz is 
not left out either. Forget the old-fashioned mimeograph. Republicans and 
Democrats maintain their own impressive media operations that enable their 
congressional members to make and beam back video press releases to their 
constituencies via satellite. 
</P>
<P>
Smith calls this "mass marketing with a home touch." The Democrats used the 
technique at their national convention in Atlanta, operating their own studio 
inside the convention center from which office holders and other prominent 
Democrats taped messages for their constituencies or conducted live satellite 
interviews with TV reporters in their home districts. With any luck, they made 
the local news. 
</P>
<P>
A favorite stage in Washington is the Capitol lawn, where tonight we see 
members of Congress in the role of propagandists for their voting philosophies 
and, not incidentally, themselves. One after another, these video hucksters 
queue up before a camera and make virtually identical statements tailored for 
local newscasts back home: "The trade bill is extremely important to this 
country and to my district. . . . " 
</P>
<P>
"And," you wish they'd add, "my own survival is extremely important to me." 
</P>
<P>
So important, perhaps, that for many members of Congress the drive to save 
one's seat is so consuming that little time or energy remains for saving the 
world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist Hedrick Smith hosts "The Power Game," 
a four-part series starting tonight on PBS. ; Photo, Smith interviews Nancy 
Reagan on the third part of "The Power Game" on Wednesday. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
